# ==============================================================================
# Reactive `for`-loop iter vars — `x.foo` inside `for x in reactive` tracks
# ==============================================================================
# When the iter source is reactive, direct member access on the iter var
# (`item.foo`, `item[0]`, `item.a.b`) is treated as reactive — the read
# is wrapped in __effect inside the per-row patch function, so in-place
# mutation updates the row without a reconciler rebuild.
#
# Not tracked (deferred — see AGENTS.md): aliases (`local = item`),
# object destructuring (`for {profile} in users`), primitive
# destructuring (`for {qty} in items`). Workaround: write `item.foo`
# directly. The negative test below pins the alias boundary.

code "reactive iter var: member access wrapped in __effect", '''
  export A = component
    items := [{qty: 1}]
    render
      for item in items
        span "#{item.qty}"
  ''', '''
